<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="736" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="736">A European species—the mountains of Central and East Europe (the eastern Carpathians, Alps) and the south of Scandinavia.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="736">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[155,309,1424,1450]" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Distribution</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[335,432,1424,1451]" captionStart="Fig. 41" captionStartId="6.[132,167,928,949]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,197,889]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[303,1284,196,888]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 41. Ranges of species of the genus Salda F. (1) S. morio Zett., (2) S. sahlbergi Reut., (3) S. splendens Jak., (4) S. henschii Reut. (orig.)." pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis box="[453,468,1425,1451]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">
<figureCitation box="[453,468,1425,1451]" captionStart="Figs. 1 – 14" captionStartId="2.[132,177,1514,1535]" captionTargetBox="[355,1231,198,1492]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[355,1232,196,1493]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1 – 14. Salda F., variability of hemielytral pattern (after Cobben, 1960, 1985; Lindskog, 1991): (1, 2) S. littoralis (L.);; (3 – 5) S. henschii Reut.; (6 – 8) S. morio Zett.; (9, 10) S. muelleri Zett.; (11 – 14) S. sahlbergi Reut." pageId="9" pageNumber="736">4</figureCitation>
</emphasis>
). The northwest of the European part of Russia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="736">
<taxonomicName box="[155,340,1511,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="henschii">
<emphasis box="[155,340,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Salda henschii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from the Vysoké Tatry Mts. Drake and Hoberlandt (1950) reduced this poorly known species to synonyms of the boreal mountain 
<taxonomicName box="[247,392,1617,1644]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahlbergi">
<emphasis box="[247,392,1617,1644]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. sahlbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was supported by their colleagues in the later publications (Cobben, 1960; Wróblewski, 1966, 1968). Later, Hoberlandt (1977) and Lindskog (1991) reinstated 
<taxonomicName box="[505,626,1722,1750]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="henschi">
<emphasis box="[505,626,1722,1750]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. henschi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a species and determined its range and the northern border of the range, which passes in Scandinavia along 60°N, being simultaneously the southern limit of the range of 
<taxonomicName box="[125,267,1863,1890]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahlbergi">
<emphasis box="[125,267,1863,1890]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. sahlbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in West Europe. These sibling (according to P. Lindskog) species clearly differ in the character of hairs on the dorsal side of the body and in the structure of the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[1111,1269,203,230]" captionStart="Figs. 15 – 24" captionStartId="3.[132,177,1234,1255]" captionTargetBox="[383,1203,204,1192]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[383,1203,196,1194]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 15 – 24. Salda F., parameres (orig.; 17 after Cobben, 1985; 21, 24 after Lindskog, 1991): (15 – 17) S. littoralis (L.), (18) S. kiritshenkoi Cobben, (19) S. muelleri Zett., (20) S. morio Zett., (21 – 23) S. sahlbergi Reut., (24) S. henschii Reut. [(15) Taimyr Peninsula, (16) Central Yakutia, (17) northern part of the area of the Sea of Okhotsk, (19) Shipitsyno Vill. (Severnaya Dvina), (20) Aldan River mouth, (22) Mongolia, (23) Kosh-Agach]." pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Figs. 21, 24</figureCitation>
) and parandria (
<figureCitation box="[821,967,238,265]" captionStart="Figs. 25 – 39" captionStartId="4.[132,177,1330,1351]" captionTargetBox="[370,1217,199,1290]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[370,1217,196,1290]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 25 – 39. Salda F., parameres (25 – 29) and parandria (30 – 37), apex of 2 nd gonapophysis (38, 39) (orig.; 25 – 28 after Cobben, 1985; 32, 34, 37, 38 after Lindskog, 1991); (25 – 27, 36) S. micans Jak.; (28, 29, 37) S. splendens Jak.; (30) S. littoralis (L.); (31) S. morio Zett.; (32) S. muelleri Zett.; (33, 34, 38) S. sahlbergi Reut.; (35, 39) S. henschii Reut. [(25, 36) Tokinskii Stanovik, (30) Taimyr Peninsula, (31) Aldan River mouth, (32) Shipitsyno Vill. (Severnaya Dvina), (34) Chersky Mt. Range]." pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Figs. 33, 35</figureCitation>
). In addition, a small tooth at the apex of the 2nd gonapophysis of the ovipositor is present in 
<taxonomicName box="[812,940,308,335]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="henschii">
<emphasis box="[812,940,308,335]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. henschii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and absent in 
<taxonomicName box="[1111,1252,308,335]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahlbergi">
<emphasis box="[1111,1252,308,335]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. sahlbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1268,1412,308,335]" captionStart="Figs. 25 – 39" captionStartId="4.[132,177,1330,1351]" captionTargetBox="[370,1217,199,1290]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[370,1217,196,1290]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 25 – 39. Salda F., parameres (25 – 29) and parandria (30 – 37), apex of 2 nd gonapophysis (38, 39) (orig.; 25 – 28 after Cobben, 1985; 32, 34, 37, 38 after Lindskog, 1991); (25 – 27, 36) S. micans Jak.; (28, 29, 37) S. splendens Jak.; (30) S. littoralis (L.); (31) S. morio Zett.; (32) S. muelleri Zett.; (33, 34, 38) S. sahlbergi Reut.; (35, 39) S. henschii Reut. [(25, 36) Tokinskii Stanovik, (30) Taimyr Peninsula, (31) Aldan River mouth, (32) Shipitsyno Vill. (Severnaya Dvina), (34) Chersky Mt. Range]." pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Figs. 38, 39</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="736">In the Russian fauna, this species was first recorded by Lindskog (1991) from a female collected in Gogland (Sur-Sari) Island of the Gulf of Finland (the specimen is deposited in the Zoological Museum of Helsinki). This is the easternmost record of the species in the northern part of its range.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="736" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="736">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[843,945,583,609]" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">Biology.</emphasis>
In the Alps, the species inhabits the subalpine belt, mainly the heathlands, and was also collected on the clay bank of a small stream in a coniferous forest (Hoberlandt, 1977). According to Lindskog (1991), the habitats of 
<taxonomicName box="[1094,1226,721,748]" class="Insecta" family="Saldidae" genus="Salda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="736" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="henschii">
<emphasis box="[1094,1226,721,748]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="736">S. henschii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar to those of the preceding species; in Sweden, the bugs were collected in a eutrophic bog, in Austria, on a pond shore, among moss and low sedge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
